parse.title: List of supreme courts by country

text.*:
Not to be confused with High Court.
This article needs additional citations for verification. Please help improve this article by adding citations to reliable sources. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (July 2009) (Learn how and when to remove this template message)
This list is incomplete; you can help by expanding it.

This is a list— by country — of the highest court (supreme court) in each country. Some countries have more than one "supreme" court.

Contents

  • 1 List of supreme courts
    • 1.1 States recognised by the United Nations
    • 1.2 States recognised by at least one United Nations member
    • 1.3 States not recognised by any United Nations members
    • 1.4 Sui generis entities
    • 1.5 International courts
  • 2 References

List of supreme courts[edit]

An asterisk (*) indicates that the court is not independent of either the legislature and/or executive of that country.

Sui generis entities[edit]

State Court(s)
 European Union European Court of Justice
 Sovereign Military Order of Malta Magistral Court of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta

International courts[edit]

There are a number of international courts that are the highest courts of appeal for the Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States (OECS), European Union (EU), and some of the countries of the Commonwealth of Nations respectively. However, the members of those organisations do sometimes have high courts of their own and their jurisdiction may be limited: for example the EU's court of justice can only interpret EU law and treaties, domestic cases cannot be appealed.

Organisation Court(s)
Benelux Union Benelux Court of Justice
 Caribbean Community Caribbean Court of Justice
Commonwealth of Nations Judicial Committee of the Privy Council
Council of Europe European Court of Human Rights
European Free Trade Association EFTA Court
Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States Eastern Caribbean Supreme Court
